ng scholars. In addition, Tantrism is not confined to any particular religion, but is a set of beliefs and practices that appears in a variety of religions, including Hinduism and Buddhism. This book explores one of the most controversial aspects of Tantra, its sources or roots, specifically in regard to Hinduism. The essays focus on the history and development of Tantra, the art history and archaeology of Tantra, the Vedas and Tantra, and texts and Tantra. Using various disciplinary and methodological approaches, from history to art history and religious studies to textual studies, scholars provide both broad overviews of the beginnings of Tantra and detailed analyses of specific texts, authors, art works, and rituals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHindu sectsxHistory. 0aTantrismxHistory. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 7aRELIGION / Antiquities & Archaeology.2bisacsh1 aBrooks, Douglas Renfrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Robert L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Robert L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCoburn, Thomas B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoudriaan, Teun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGupta, Lina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarper, Katherine Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarper, Katherine Anne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHudson, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoshi, M. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLorenzen, David N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcEvilley,